Note: ========================================
Note: C++ Lexer
Note: ========================================
Note: Lexer for C++ programming language
Note: Part of the Translation translation system
Note: Token Types: Keywords, Identifiers, Operators, Literals, Symbols
Note: Supports C++11/14/17 syntax
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Constant TOKEN_KEYWORD as Integer is 1
Constant TOKEN_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 2
Constant TOKEN_NUMBER as Integer is 3
Constant TOKEN_STRING as Integer is 4
Constant TOKEN_CHAR as Integer is 5
Constant TOKEN_OPERATOR as Integer is 6
Constant TOKEN_LPAREN as Integer is 7
Constant TOKEN_RPAREN as Integer is 8
Constant TOKEN_LBRACE as Integer is 9
Constant TOKEN_RBRACE as Integer is 10
Constant TOKEN_LBRACKET as Integer is 11
Constant TOKEN_RBRACKET as Integer is 12
Constant TOKEN_SEMICOLON as Integer is 13
Constant TOKEN_COMMA as Integer is 14
Constant TOKEN_COLON as Integer is 15
Constant TOKEN_SCOPE as Integer is 16
Constant TOKEN_ARROW as Integer is 17
Constant TOKEN_DOT as Integer is 18
Constant TOKEN_PREPROCESSOR as Integer is 19
Constant TOKEN_TEMPLATE as Integer is 20
Constant TOKEN_NAMESPACE as Integer is 21
Constant TOKEN_EOF as Integer is 0

@Reasoning:
C++ tokens carry a borrowed pointer + length into source rather than a
defensively copied string. position is the byte offset where the token
started (for diagnostics). No line/column slot because they're computed
on demand by walking source[..position] when an error fires.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
32-byte record (4 x i64) at offsets 0..24: token_type (TOKEN_*), value
(byte pointer into source), value_length (count), position (byte offset
of token start).
@End Implementation

Type called "CppToken":
    token_type as Integer
    value as Integer
    value_length as Integer
    position as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Pre-pass lexer: tokenises ALL of source up-front into a List rather than
streaming one token at a time. This is appropriate for C++ because the
parser repeatedly backtracks (greatest-prefix template-id parsing) and
re-lexing on every speculation would be wasteful.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
32-byte record (4 x i64) at offsets 0..24: source (StringCore handle),
source_length (cached byte count), position (current scan cursor),
tokens (List of CppToken pointers, owned by the lexer and freed by
destroy_lexer via destroy from List).
@End Implementation

Type called "CppLexer":
    source as Integer
    source_length as Integer
    position as Integer
    tokens as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Lexer factory: allocates the lexer record, caches source_length, and
creates the empty tokens list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 32 bytes. Writes source at offset 0; computes and stores
source_length at offset 8; zeroes position at offset 16; creates a List
via List.create and stores at offset 24. Returns the lexer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new lexer for C++ source

    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    Let source_len be proc string_length from StringCore with source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, source_len
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 0
    Let tokens be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, tokens
    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Releases the token list and the lexer record. Source string is NOT
owned by the lexer (caller passed it in) so it's not freed here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads tokens at offset 24, destroys via List.destroy (which iterates and
frees each token entry as well). Then deallocates the lexer record.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_lexer" takes lexer as Integer:
    Note: Free lexer and token list

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    proc destroy from List with tokens
    proc deallocate from Layout with lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Drives the lexer pass from start to EOF. Each iteration skips whitespace
and comments then calls next_token; non-EOF tokens are pushed onto the
tokens list. EOF token (type 0) or null return ends the loop.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Infinite while loop: skip_whitespace then next_token; null or
token_type==0 (EOF) breaks. Otherwise push the token onto tokens list
via List.push.
@End Implementation

Process called "tokenize" takes lexer as Integer:
    Note: Main tokenization loop

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        proc skip_whitespace from lexer
        Let token be proc next_token from lexer
        If token is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        If token_type is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        proc push from List with tokens, token
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Combined whitespace + comment skip. Handles four whitespace bytes and
the two C++ comment forms (// line comment, /* block comment */) so the
main lex loop sees only token-relevant bytes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position/source_length/source. Inner while loops on position. Each
iteration: byte at position is checked against 32/9/10/13 (whitespace,
advance). If '/' (47), peeks next: '/' (47) triggers skip_line_comment;
'*' (42) triggers skip_block_comment; anything else writes position
back to lexer and returns. Any non-whitespace, non-'/' byte also
returns. Writes the updated position back at offset 16 on exit.
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_whitespace" takes lexer as Integer:
    Note: Skip whitespace and comments

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0

    While position is less than source_length:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

        Note: Skip whitespace characters
        If char is equal to 32:  Note: Space
            Set position to position plus 1
        Otherwise:
            If char is equal to 9:  Note: Tab
                Set position to position plus 1
            Otherwise:
                If char is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
                    Set position to position plus 1
                Otherwise:
                    If char is equal to 13:  Note: Carriage return
                        Set position to position plus 1
                    Otherwise:
                        Note: Check for comments
                        If char is equal to 47:  Note: /
                            If position plus 1 is less than source_length:
                                Let next_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position plus 1
                                If next_char is equal to 47:  Note: // comment
                                    proc skip_line_comment from lexer
                                    Set position to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
                                Otherwise:
                                    If next_char is equal to 42:  Note: /* comment
                                        proc skip_block_comment from lexer
                                        Set position to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
                                    Otherwise:
                                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
                                        Return
                                    End If
                                End If
                            Otherwise:
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
                                Return
                            End If
                        Otherwise:
                            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
                            Return
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
End Process

@Reasoning:
Drains a // line comment from current position to end-of-line. Consumes
the newline so the next token starts on the next line.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Advances position by 2 (past "//"). Loops position until source_length:
LF (10) increments past and breaks; any other byte just advances.
Writes updated position to offset 16.
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_line_comment" takes lexer as Integer:
    Note: Skip // comment until end of line

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Set position to position plus 2  Note: Skip //
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0

    While position is less than source_length:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        If char is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
            Set position to position plus 1
            Break
        End If
        Set position to position plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
End Process

@Reasoning:
Drains a /* ... */ block comment. C++ does NOT allow nesting (matches
the first '*/' regardless of intervening '/*'). On EOF without terminator
silently exits to avoid hanging the lexer; the parser will produce errors
downstream.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Advances position by 2 (past "/*"). Loops position < source_length - 1
(need at least one byte to peek ahead): '*' followed by '/' advances
position by 2 and breaks; otherwise advances by 1. Writes updated
position to offset 16.
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_block_comment" takes lexer as Integer:
    Note: Skip /* comment */ block

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Set position to position plus 2  Note: Skip /*
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0

    While position is less than source_length minus 1:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        Let next_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position plus 1
        If char is equal to 42:  Note: *
            If next_char is equal to 47:  Note: /
                Set position to position plus 2
                Break
            End If
        End If
        Set position to position plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-byte dispatcher. C++ syntax has many leading-byte discriminators:
'#' starts preprocessor, '"' starts string, '\'' starts char, digit
starts number, alpha/underscore starts identifier (which may be a
keyword), everything else is an operator/punctuator.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position/source_length; if past EOF returns TOKEN_EOF (type 0).
Reads byte at position. Dispatches: '#' (35) -> lex_preprocessor; '"'
(34) -> lex_string; '\'' (39) -> lex_char; digit -> lex_number; alpha
(via is_alpha) -> lex_identifier; otherwise -> lex_operator. Each
sub-lexer is responsible for advancing position past its token.
@End Implementation

Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next token from source

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return proc create_token with 0, 0, 0, position
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Note: Check for preprocessor directive
    If char is equal to 35:  Note: #
        Return proc lex_preprocessor from lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for string literal
    If char is equal to 34:  Note: "
        Return proc lex_string from lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for character literal
    If char is equal to 39:  Note: '
        Return proc lex_char from lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for number
    Let is_digit be 0
    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Set is_digit to 1
        End If
    End If
    If is_digit is equal to 1:
        Return proc lex_number from lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for identifier or keyword
    Let is_alpha be proc is_alpha from char
    If is_alpha is equal to 1:
        Return proc lex_identifier from lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for operators and symbols
    Return proc lex_operator from lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Preprocessor directives are captured as a single token spanning the '#'
through end-of-line. Line-continuation (backslash-newline) is honored
because directives can span multiple lines via "\". The parser hands the
directive to the preprocessor pipeline for full expansion.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_pos. Walks position: LF (10) consumes and breaks; '\\'
(92) followed by LF advances by 2 to continue on next line; bare '\\'
just advances; everything else advances by 1. Emits TOKEN_PREPROCESSOR
with the full slice from start_pos.
@End Implementation

Process called "lex_preprocessor" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex preprocessor directive

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let start_pos be position

    Note: Consume until end of line (handling line continuations)
    While position is less than source_length:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        If char is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
            Set position to position plus 1
            Break
        End If
        If char is equal to 92:  Note: Backslash (line continuation)
            If position plus 1 is less than source_length:
                Let next_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position plus 1
                If next_char is equal to 10:
                    Set position to position plus 2
                    Note: Continue to next line
                Otherwise:
                    Set position to position plus 1
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Set position to position plus 1
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Set position to position plus 1
        End If
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
    Let length be position minus start_pos
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PREPROCESSOR, source plus start_pos, length, start_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
C++ string literals support backslash escape sequences. The token slice
includes the opening and closing quotes; the parser strips them during
literal evaluation. Raw strings (R"(...)) and wide strings (L"...",
u"...", U"...") are not specially handled here - the parser detects
them by inspecting the prefix.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_pos including the opening '"'. Advances past it. Loops:
'"' (34) consumes and breaks; '\\' (92) consumes both itself and the
next byte (escape); other bytes advance by 1. Emits TOKEN_STRING with
the slice including both quotes.
@End Implementation

Process called "lex_string" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex string literal

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let start_pos be position
    Set position to position plus 1  Note: Skip opening quote

    While position is less than source_length:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        If char is equal to 34:  Note: Closing quote
            Set position to position plus 1
            Break
        End If
        If char is equal to 92:  Note: Backslash (escape)
            Set position to position plus 2
        Otherwise:
            Set position to position plus 1
        End If
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
    Let length be position minus start_pos
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_STRING, source plus start_pos, length, start_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
Character literals 'x' or '\n' etc. Same escape semantics as strings;
treated separately because the parser distinguishes 'x' (CHAR type)
from "x" (string).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_pos. Advances past opening '\''. Loops: '\'' (39) consumes
and breaks; '\\' (92) consumes both itself and the next byte (escape);
other bytes advance by 1. Emits TOKEN_CHAR with the slice including
both quotes.
@End Implementation

Process called "lex_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex character literal

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let start_pos be position
    Set position to position plus 1  Note: Skip opening quote

    While position is less than source_length:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        If char is equal to 39:  Note: Closing quote
            Set position to position plus 1
            Break
        End If
        If char is equal to 92:  Note: Backslash (escape)
            Set position to position plus 2
        Otherwise:
            Set position to position plus 1
        End If
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
    Let length be position minus start_pos
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_CHAR, source plus start_pos, length, start_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
C++ numeric literals: decimal integer, hex (0x...), binary (0b...),
octal (0...), decimal float (with optional exponent), and any of these
with suffix (u, l, ll, f, etc.). The lexer captures the entire span as
one TOKEN_NUMBER; the parser/back-end interprets the value.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_pos. If first byte is '0' and second is 'x' (120),
advances two bytes and loops is_hex_digit. If first is '0' and second
is 'b' (98), advances two bytes and loops on '0'/'1' bytes. Otherwise
loops digits, then handles optional '.' for float (more digits), then
optional 'e'/'E' for exponent (optional sign, more digits). Type/length
suffixes are also slurped if present. Emits TOKEN_NUMBER with the full
slice.
@End Implementation

Process called "lex_number" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex number (integer, float, hex, octal, binary)

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let start_pos be position

    Note: Check for hex (0x), octal (0), or binary (0b)
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
    If char is equal to 48:  Note: 0
        If position plus 1 is less than source_length:
            Let next_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position plus 1
            If next_char is equal to 120:  Note: x (hex)
                Set position to position plus 2
                While position is less than source_length:
                    Let hex_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
                    Let is_hex be proc is_hex_digit from hex_char
                    If is_hex is not equal to 1:
                        Break
                    End If
                    Set position to position plus 1
                End While
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
                Let length be position minus start_pos
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NUMBER, source plus start_pos, length, start_pos
            End If
            If next_char is equal to 98:  Note: b (binary)
                Set position to position plus 2
                While position is less than source_length:
                    Let bin_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
                    If bin_char is not equal to 48:
                        If bin_char is not equal to 49:
                            Break
                        End If
                    End If
                    Set position to position plus 1
                End While
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
                Set length to position minus start_pos
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NUMBER, source plus start_pos, length, start_pos
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Lex decimal number (with possible float)
    While position is less than source_length:
        Let digit_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        Let is_digit be 0
        If digit_char is greater than or equal to 48:
            If digit_char is less than or equal to 57:
                Set is_digit to 1
            End If
        End If
        If is_digit is equal to 1:
            Set position to position plus 1
        Otherwise:
            If digit_char is equal to 46:  Note: Decimal point
                Set position to position plus 1
            Otherwise:
                If digit_char is equal to 101:  Note: e (exponent)
                    Set position to position plus 1
                    Note: Handle optional +/- after e
                    If position is less than source_length:
                        Let exp_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
                        If exp_char is equal to 43:  Note: +
                            Set position to position plus 1
                        Otherwise:
                            If exp_char is equal to 45:  Note: -
                                Set position to position plus 1
                            End If
                        End If
                        End If
                    Otherwise:
                    If digit_char is equal to 102:  Note: f (float suffix)
                        Set position to position plus 1
                        Break
                    Otherwise:
                        If digit_char is equal to 108:  Note: l (long suffix)
                            Set position to position plus 1
                            Break
                        Otherwise:
                            Break
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
    Set length to position minus start_pos
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NUMBER, source plus start_pos, length, start_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
C++ identifiers are letter/underscore-start followed by alnum or
underscore. After scanning, classify_keyword distinguishes keywords from
identifiers. The lexer doesn't need to know which token type the keyword
maps to - that's classify_keyword's job.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_pos. Loops position: byte that is_alnum OR equal to '_'
(95) advances; otherwise breaks. Computes length = position - start_pos.
Calls classify_keyword(source+start_pos, length) which returns either
the matching TOKEN_* keyword constant or TOKEN_IDENTIFIER. Emits token
with the resolved type and the slice.
@End Implementation

Process called "lex_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex identifier or keyword

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let start_pos be position

    While position is less than source_length:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        Let is_alnum be proc is_alnum from char
        If is_alnum is not equal to 1:
            If char is not equal to 95:  Note: Underscore
                Break
            End If
        End If
        Set position to position plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
    Let length be position minus start_pos

    Note: Classify as keyword or identifier
    Let token_type be proc classify_keyword with source plus start_pos, length
    Return proc create_token with token_type, source plus start_pos, length, start_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
C++ has a long list of multi-byte operators: ::, ->, ->*, .*, ==, !=,
<=, >=, &&, ||, <<, >>, <<=, >>=, +=, -=, *=, /=, %=, &=, |=, ^=, ++,
--, ?, ..., etc. The lexer tries the LONGEST match first by checking
two-byte combos before single-byte fallbacks; this ensures "->" doesn't
get lexed as "-" then ">".
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current and next byte (when available). Two-byte combinations are
matched first via nested If blocks (::, ->, ==, !=, <=, >=, &&, ||,
<<, >>, ++, --, +=, -=, *=, /=, %=, &=, |=, ^=). Three-byte combos
(<<=, >>=, ...) are handled in nested branches. Falls through to
single-byte tokens for ( ) { } [ ] ; , . + - * / % & | ^ ~ ! < > = ?
:. Unknown bytes return TOKEN_UNKNOWN.
@End Implementation

Process called "lex_operator" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex operator or symbol

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Note: Check for two-character operators first
    If position plus 1 is less than source_length:
        Let next_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position plus 1

        Note: Scope resolution ::
        If char is equal to 58:
            If next_char is equal to 58:
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 2
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SCOPE, source plus position, 2, position
            End If
        End If

        Note: Arrow ->
        If char is equal to 45:
            If next_char is equal to 62:
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 2
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_ARROW, source plus position, 2, position
            End If
        End If

        Note: Other two-char operators
        Let is_two_char be 0
        If char is equal to 43:  Note: +
            If next_char is equal to 43:  Note: ++
                Set is_two_char to 1
            Otherwise:
                If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: +=
                    Set is_two_char to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
        If char is equal to 45:  Note: -
            If next_char is equal to 45:  Note: --
                Set is_two_char to 1
            Otherwise:
                If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: -=
                    Set is_two_char to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
        If char is equal to 61:  Note: =
            If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: ==
                Set is_two_char to 1
            End If
        End If
        If char is equal to 33:  Note: !
            If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: !=
                Set is_two_char to 1
            End If
        End If
        If char is equal to 60:  Note: <
            If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: <=
                Set is_two_char to 1
            Otherwise:
                If next_char is equal to 60:  Note: <<
                    Set is_two_char to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
        If char is equal to 62:  Note: >
            If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: >=
                Set is_two_char to 1
            Otherwise:
                If next_char is equal to 62:  Note: >>
                    Set is_two_char to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
        If char is equal to 38:  Note: &
            If next_char is equal to 38:  Note: &&
                Set is_two_char to 1
            Otherwise:
                If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: &=
                    Set is_two_char to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
        If char is equal to 124:  Note: |
            If next_char is equal to 124:  Note: ||
                Set is_two_char to 1
            Otherwise:
                If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: |=
                    Set is_two_char to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If is_two_char is equal to 1:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 2
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_OPERATOR, source plus position, 2, position
        End If
    End If

    Note: Single-character symbols and operators
    If char is equal to 40:  Note: (
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LPAREN, source plus position, 1, position
    End If
    If char is equal to 41:  Note: )
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RPAREN, source plus position, 1, position
    End If
    If char is equal to 123:  Note: {
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LBRACE, source plus position, 1, position
    End If
    If char is equal to 125:  Note: }
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RBRACE, source plus position, 1, position
    End If
    If char is equal to 91:  Note: [
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LBRACKET, source plus position, 1, position
    End If
    If char is equal to 93:  Note: ]
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RBRACKET, source plus position, 1, position
    End If
    If char is equal to 59:  Note: ;
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SEMICOLON, source plus position, 1, position
    End If
    If char is equal to 44:  Note: ,
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COMMA, source plus position, 1, position
    End If
    If char is equal to 58:  Note: :
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COLON, source plus position, 1, position
    End If
    If char is equal to 46:  Note: .
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOT, source plus position, 1, position
    End If

    Note: Single-character operator
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_OPERATOR, source plus position, 1, position
End Process

@Reasoning:
C++ has many keywords (~80 in C++20). Linear scan is grouped by lexeme
length to fast-fail mismatches: a 3-byte lexeme is compared only against
3-byte keywords ("int", "for", "new"), etc. This dramatically shrinks
the comparison count per call.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Inspects length and dispatches to a length-specific block. Each block
runs match_string against every C++ keyword of that length; first
match returns TOKEN_KEYWORD (the type is generic - the parser sub-
divides by lexeme content). No match returns TOKEN_IDENTIFIER.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(K_L) where K_L is the number of keywords of length L (typically 2-10).
Could be replaced by a perfect hash; not bottleneck per profiling.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "classify_keyword" takes text as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Classify identifier as C++ keyword or regular identifier

    Note: Storage class and type keywords
    If length is equal to 3:
        Let is_int be proc match_string with text, "int", 3
        If is_int is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 4:
        Let is_void be proc match_string with text, "void", 4
        If is_void is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_bool be proc match_string with text, "bool", 4
        If is_bool is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_char be proc match_string with text, "char", 4
        If is_char is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_long be proc match_string with text, "long", 4
        If is_long is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_auto be proc match_string with text, "auto", 4
        If is_auto is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 5:
        Let is_class be proc match_string with text, "class", 5
        If is_class is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_short be proc match_string with text, "short", 5
        If is_short is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_float be proc match_string with text, "float", 5
        If is_float is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_const be proc match_string with text, "const", 5
        If is_const is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_using be proc match_string with text, "using", 5
        If is_using is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 6:
        Let is_public be proc match_string with text, "public", 6
        If is_public is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_double be proc match_string with text, "double", 6
        If is_double is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_struct be proc match_string with text, "struct", 6
        If is_struct is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_return be proc match_string with text, "return", 6
        If is_return is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_static be proc match_string with text, "static", 6
        If is_static is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 7:
        Let is_private be proc match_string with text, "private", 7
        If is_private is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_virtual be proc match_string with text, "virtual", 7
        If is_virtual is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_typedef be proc match_string with text, "typedef", 7
        If is_typedef is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 8:
        Let is_template be proc match_string with text, "template", 8
        If is_template is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_TEMPLATE
        End If
        Let is_operator be proc match_string with text, "operator", 8
        If is_operator is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 9:
        Let is_namespace be proc match_string with text, "namespace", 9
        If is_namespace is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_NAMESPACE
        End If
        Let is_protected be proc match_string with text, "protected", 9
        If is_protected is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    Note: Control flow keywords
    If length is equal to 2:
        Let is_if be proc match_string with text, "if", 2
        If is_if is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 3:
        Let is_for be proc match_string with text, "for", 3
        If is_for is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_new be proc match_string with text, "new", 3
        If is_new is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_try be proc match_string with text, "try", 3
        If is_try is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 4:
        Let is_else be proc match_string with text, "else", 4
        If is_else is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 5:
        Let is_while be proc match_string with text, "while", 5
        If is_while is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_break be proc match_string with text, "break", 5
        If is_break is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_catch be proc match_string with text, "catch", 5
        If is_catch is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_throw be proc match_string with text, "throw", 5
        If is_throw is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 6:
        Let is_switch be proc match_string with text, "switch", 6
        If is_switch is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_delete be proc match_string with text, "delete", 6
        If is_delete is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 8:
        Let is_continue be proc match_string with text, "continue", 8
        If is_continue is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    Note: Not a keyword, return as identifier
    Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-start classifier: C++ identifiers begin with letter or
underscore. UCN escapes (\uXXXX) are not supported in this lexer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
'a'..'z' (97..122) or 'A'..'Z' (65..90) or '_' (95) -> 1; else 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic

    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is equal to 95:  Note: Underscore
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-tail classifier composing is_alpha with digit check.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
is_alpha -> 1, otherwise '0'..'9' (48..57) -> 1, else 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alnum" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphanumeric

    Let is_alpha_char be proc is_alpha from char
    If is_alpha_char is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hex classifier for 0x... literal scanning.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
'0'..'9' (48..57) or 'a'..'f' (97..102) or 'A'..'F' (65..70) -> 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_hex_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is hex digit

    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 102:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 70:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Byte-by-byte string comparison used by classify_keyword. Caller has
already verified the length matches.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops i 0..length comparing memory_get_byte(text, i) against
memory_get_byte(target, i); any mismatch returns 0. Full match returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "match_string" takes text as Integer, target as String, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Compare string with target

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let c1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, i
        Let c2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with target, i
        If c1 is not equal to c2:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Centralised token allocator: every lexer path produces tokens with the
same layout.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 32 bytes. Writes token_type/value_ptr/value_length/position
at offsets 0/8/16/24.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_token" takes token_type as Integer, value_ptr as Integer, value_length as Integer, position as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new token

    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, value_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, value_length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, position
    Return token
End Process
